<br>
Was I calling him a homosexual because he did something stupid?  No, how &quot;I&quot; interpret it is that it was an extremely lame and odd thing to do.  The English vocabulary has adopted many words to different situations.  Such is the word fuck - don't get me started as Adam Sandler can best sum it up in &quot;Uses of the word Fuck.mp3&quot;<br>
<br>
And I do agree with you Halo about the mentality of EC almost all of the time now it seems.  Last night I got to be in the middle of a pirate and friends protecting their &quot;trizzure&quot;.  Shouts every 20seconds with &quot;YAR!&quot; and the such continued for a good hour.  I do believe Teabaggin' was mentioned <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :| --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/indifferent.gif ALT=":|"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
As for Palimax's comment reguarding societies views:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Yes. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I agree.  Sure he may not speak for a society as a whole, but folks - this isn't a problem that just came up.  A society as a whole DOES have this mentality.  There are what, 250 million in the USA, and very frequently a death based solely on sexual orientation happens, as well as many other crimes/actions take part such as the Southern Church Burnings.  Although not necissarily gay related, these actions show just how neanderthalic our &quot;modern&quot; society is. Granted not EVERY single person will have this gay bashing view.  We are on a moderated message board - maybe 1% of the American population will read this and share our views.  What about the other 99% - left to fight it out like dogs...<br>
<br>
That's how I feel... <p><img src="http://testreject.iwarp.com/scarecrow1.gif"></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uafierra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Afierra</A> at: 1/22/02 8:10:31 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=nydia>Nydia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/22/02 9:14:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=837.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Deviant, evolution, get over it?</span><hr size=1> Dear Halo: Since you are playing rather fast and loose with your definition of 'society' in your original post, I would have to say that *both* of your statements, as you posed them, are true.  In most societies, by and large, (including Calvinist-decended America), homosexuality is considered 'deviant' by a large segment of the population, but it is also undeniably true that homoexuality has been with us throughout recorded history, so it would be a stretch to call it 'unnatural'.  And, homosexuality has been more-or-less accepted, or at least given a 'niche', in many societies that don't appear, on the surface, to tolerate it.  It is only in the West, in the past fifty years that we have paid more *conscious* attention to homosexuality, but societies such as India have had an official 'third gender' (hermaphrodite, which encompasses everything from eunuchs to transvestites to effeminite male homosexuals) for centuries. <br>
<br>
But since what you really seem to be interested in is the server population's *opinion* of homosexuality...<br>
<br>
I think that a small, but significant, portion of the population is simply born, (either genetically, or by their hormonal/prenatal environment), to be homosexual, bisexual, or transgendered.  There is a pretty hefty body of evidence in animal models to back this up, from population surveys of mating pairs of migratory birds, to Dr. John Money's (at John's Hopkins) prenatal hormone studies on sheep.  In my opinion, to classify these people as 'deviant' would be as rediculous as classifying people with, say, an RH-negative blood type (rare, and definitely *not* a survival advantage, but persisting in the population as a normally fixed trait regardless) as deviants.  I think the increased 'official' awareness and tolererance of gay, bi, and trans folks can only be a *good* thing, as it addresses an issue that has always existed in our society anyway.  And to mangle a famous quote, if we're not doing it out in the street and frightening the horses, what does it matter what adults do in the privacy of their romantic lives, anyway?<br>
<br>
I recently read in the newspaper that a high level government official in Norway just married his long term companion, and a minimum of fuss was made about it.  I think that this is as it should be, and that people should simply 'live and let live' as far as other folks sexual/gender orientations go...<br>
<br>
I could go a lot longer on this topic, but think I will save it for the (probably inevitable) replies.<br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
Nydia Ywalmoriel<br>
Autonomous Collective<br>
